## International and Domestic Trends

| Country/State           | Prisoner Voting Policy                         | Notes                                                                                     |
|------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| United States          | Mostly disenfranchised; Maine & Vermont allow | 6.1 million disenfranchised due to felony convictions; only two states allow voting in prison ([Sentencing Project, 2019](https://www.sentencingproject.org/news/opinion-prisoners-allowed-vote/)) |
| United Kingdom         | Blanket ban on prisoner voting                 | ECtHR ruled blanket ban illegal; government maintains ban as of 2015 ([YouGov, 2015](https://yougov.co.uk/topics/politics/articles-reports/2015/02/06/update-attitudes-prison-voting-viva-civic-death-pe)) |
| European Union         | Generally allow prisoner voting                 | Most democracies allow prisoner voting rights ([Writolay, n.d.](https://writolay.com/prisoners-allowed-to-vote/)) |
| Canada                 | Allow prisoner voting                           | Prisoners retain voting rights ([Writolay, n.d.](https://writolay.com/prisoners-allowed-to-vote/)) |

