## Impact of Prisoner Disenfranchisement

- Approximately 6.1 million people in the U.S. are disenfranchised due to felony convictions, including 1.3 million currently incarcerated ([Sentencing Project, 2019](https://www.sentencingproject.org/news/opinion-prisoners-allowed-vote/)).

- Disenfranchisement disproportionately affects ethnic minorities, exacerbating social inequalities and political disempowerment ([Easton, Black & Dhami, 2012](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09627251.2012.751247)).

- Loss of voting rights can hinder reintegration by alienating former prisoners from civic life and reducing political participation post-release ([Politico, 2016](https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/06/prisoners-convicts-felons-inmates-right-to-vote-enfranchise-criminal-justice-voting-rights-213979/)).

---

## Conclusion and Opinion

Based on the comprehensive review of legal rulings, empirical research, ethical considerations, and international practices, the evidence strongly supports allowing people in prison to vote. The right to vote is a fundamental democratic right that should not be arbitrarily revoked as part of criminal punishment. Disenfranchisement undermines democratic principles, disproportionately harms marginalized communities, and impedes rehabilitation and reintegration.

Allowing prisoners to vote would enhance democratic inclusion, give voice to an often overlooked constituency, and potentially improve prison conditions by holding the system accountable to those it affects most directly. Practical concerns about election integrity and administrative challenges are manageable through established mechanisms such as absentee or mail-in voting in prisoners' home districts.

Therefore, it is recommended that blanket bans on prisoner voting be abolished, and policies be implemented to facilitate voting access for incarcerated individuals, consistent with democratic values and human rights.

